    "The outputs of the individual models are then combined to yield the overall output of the ensemble prediction model M, expressed asM: пЈұ пЈҙ пЈҙ пЈҙ пЈҙ пЈІ пЈҙ пЈҙ пЈҙ пЈҙ пЈі M [i]: x [i] (k + 1) = f [i] x [i] (k), u(k) y [i] (k) = g [i] x [i] (k), u(k) (5a) y(k) = n i=1 О» [i] (k)y [i] (k)(5b)where f [i] and g [i] are generic parametric functions characterizing model M [i], whose parameters are identified from the datasetD [i].",
    "Furthermore, x [i] вҲҲ R n [i]x, y [i] вҲҲ R ny are the state and output variables of the i-th model, respectively, and y вҲҲ R ny is the output of the ensemble obtained through a convex combination of y [i], defined by О» [i] вҲҲ R вүҘ0, for i = 1,..., n. Two main challenges arise when employing a data-based ensemble prediction model within an MPC framework:1) determining an appropriate rule to combine the outputs of the individual models through the weights О» [i], which, for optimality, should vary along the prediction window as a function of available variables; 2) estimating the states of the data-based ensemble model while enforcing state constraints.",
    "MPC WITH MAHALANOBIS DISTANCE-BASED ENSEMBLE MODELThe first contribution of this work is an MPC regulator embedding a data-based ensemble model for prediction, where the outputs of each ensemble component are combined according to the statistical proximity between the optimised inputs and those used to train the specific model.",
    "This strategy is inspired by [26], where, however, control design and state estimation for ensembles are not addressed.Considering a sampling time П„ and a prediction horizon H, at each time instant t = kП„, with k вҲҲ N, the following MPC problem is solved according to the receding horizon strategy:P MPC {x [i] (k)} iвҲҲN, d = min Е©(h) k+H h=k L(h) (6a) s.t.",
    "вҲҖh вҲҲ {k,..., k + H} x [i] (h + 1) = f [i] x [i] (h), u(h), i вҲҲ N, (6b) y [i] (h) = g [i] x [i] (h), u(h), i вҲҲ N,(6c)y(h) = n i=1 О» [i] (h)y [i] (h),(6d)x [i] (k) = x[i] (k), i вҲҲ N, (6e) x [i] (h + 1) вҲҲ X, i вҲҲ N, (6f) Е©(h) вҲҲ U, (6g) y(h) вҲҲ Y(h),(6h)whered = d вҠӨ (k)... d вҠӨ (k +H -1)вҠӨ are known estimates of the external disturbances that enter the model input, i.e., u(h) = Е©(h) вҠӨ d вҠӨ (h) вҠӨ."
